	<presentation external="api-introduction.pdf">
		<title>Understanding APIs</title>
		<toc class="abstract">An introduction to terminology and value of APIs. Including the definitions of private, public and partner APIs.</toc>
	</presentation>
	<presentation external="api-business.pdf">
		<title>API Business Models</title>
		<toc class="abstract">A case study driven exploration of the six business drivers for API programs: revenue, reach, growth, intelligence, innovation and compliance.</toc>
	</presentation>
	<presentation external="api-implementation.pdf">
		<title>Implementing APIs in Large Organizations</title>
		<toc class="abstract">What you need to know to succeed with an API program, including organizational design and API lifecycle considerations.</toc>
	</presentation>
	<presentation id="api-styles">
		<title>API Styles</title>
		<toc class="abstract">APIs as a medium for communications can follow different styles. Knowing the styles, picking the ones that are a good choice for a given scenario, and establishing an internal API stylebook are important aspects of an API strategy.</toc>
		<toc class="resources"><a href="http://dret.net/netdret/publications#pau09a" title='Cesare Pautasso and Erik Wilde, "Why is the Web Loosely Coupled? A Multi-Faceted Metric for Service Design", 18th International World Wide Web Conference (WWW2009), Madrid, Spain, April 2009'>Loose Coupling</a>&#160;· <a href="http://apistylebook.com/" title='Arnaud Lauret, "API Stylebook"'>API Stylebook</a></toc>
